Here’s a draft of a broad, “infrastructure” claim you might use as a starting point for a provisional filing. It’s phrased roughly in the “system” style that captures the essential building blocks of your platform while leaving room for tweaks. Remember—this is just a template; a registered patent attorney can tighten the language and make sure the claim scope is enforceable.

> **Claim 1**  
> A patient‑clinician interaction system comprising:  
> • a patient module that accepts authenticated symptom data and contact information from a mobile or web interface;  
> • an automated triage module that processes the entered symptom data using a rule‑based or machine‑learning algorithm to assign an urgency score and recommended next steps;  
> • a clinician notification module that delivers the triage output and patient details to a clinician’s device in real‑time, optionally scheduling a virtual or in‑person appointment;  
> • an integration interface that retrieves patient demographics, medication history, and prior visit data from an electronic health record system, and uploads the system’s interaction logs back to the record;  
> • a secure data‑handling component that encrypts all patient data at rest and in transit, authenticated exchanges, and ensures compliance with HIPAA requirements;  
> and wherein the modules are coordinated by a central management engine that enforces user access rights, audit trails, and concurrency controls, thereby enabling direct, immediate communication between patients and clinicians without the need for intermediate administrative steps.

You can add dependent claims later that point to specific algorithms, UI flows, or billing workflows. The key is that the independent claim speaks to the whole architecture so that any minimal deviation still falls under the scope. Once you file the provisional, a patent professional can refine this into a full‐scope claim set that balances breadth with specificity. Good luck!
